  "footnotes": [
    "Kingdom of Abkhazia (c.778–1008): the Abkhazian kingdom expanded from its northwestern base to eventually unite most of western Georgia; its ruling Anosid dynasty presided over a Christian kingdom that became a major cultural center; the kingdom merged into the unified Kingdom of Georgia under Bagrat III in 1008",
    "Kingdom of Georgia — Golden Age (1008–1220): under David IV 'the Builder' (1089–1125) who expelled the Seljuks and captured Tbilisi (1122), and Queen Tamar (1184–1213) who presided over Georgia's greatest territorial extent stretching from the Black Sea to the Caspian; Rustaveli composed 'The Knight in the Panther's Skin' at her court; the kingdom was devastated by the Mongol invasions beginning in 1220",
    "Tao-Klarjeti (813–1001): a Georgian principality in the southwestern highlands (today's northeastern Turkey and southwestern Georgia) that played a pivotal role in unifying the Georgian kingdoms; the Bagratid rulers of Tao ceded the principality to Byzantium in 1001, but Bagrat III used the inheritance to complete Georgian unification",
    "Samtskhe (Meskheti) (c.1268–1625): a powerful southwestern Georgian principality (Atabagship) that controlled the routes between Anatolia and the Caucasus; gradually drawn into Ottoman orbit and formally became an Ottoman province (Çıldır Eyaleti) in 1625 after conversion of the ruling family to Islam",
    "Dark Ages of Georgia (15th–18th c.): repeated Timurid invasions (8 campaigns, 1386–1403), Turkmen raids, and then Ottoman–Safavid partition reduced Georgia's population and devastated its cities; the unified kingdom fragmented into Kartli, Kakheti, Imereti and smaller principalities fighting for survival",
    "Democratic Republic of Georgia (1918–1921): the first modern Georgian state adopted a democratic constitution; a brief war with Armenia over Lori district ended in ceasefire; Soviet Russia invaded in February 1921 and incorporated Georgia into the Transcaucasian SFSR by 1922"
  ]
}
